The main purpose of our analysis is to predict who is more likely to default on their credit card loans, so that the bank may be able to prevent the loss by providing the customer with alternative options.

So, the variables we have are:
ID - Client number
CODE_GENDER - Gender
FLAG_OWN_CAR - Is there a car
FLAG_OWN_REALTY - Is there a property
CNT_CHILDREN - Number of children
AMT_INCOME_TOTAL - Annual income
NAME_INCOME_TYPE - Income category
NAME_EDUCATION_TYPE - Education level
NAME_FAMILY_STATUS - Marital status
NAME_HOUSING_TYPE - Way of living
DAYS_BIRTH - Birthday - Count backwards from current day (0), -1 means yesterday
DAYS_EMPLOYED - Start date of employment - Count backwards from current day(0). If positive, it means the person currently unemployed.
FLAG_MOBIL - Is there a mobile phone
FLAG_WORK_PHONE - Is there a work phone
FLAG_PHONE - Is there a phone
FLAG_EMAIL - Is there an email
OCCUPATION_TYPE - Occupation
CNT_FAM_MEMBERS - Family size
MONTHS_BALANCE - Record month - The month of the extracted data is the starting point, backwards, 0 is the current month, -1 is the previous month, and so on
STATUS - Status - 0: 1-29 days past due 1: 30-59 days past due 2: 60-89 days overdue 3: 90-119 days overdue 4: 120-149 days overdue 5: Overdue or bad debts, write-offs for more than 150 days C: paid off that month X: No loan for the month

However, we still have three problems to solve:
1. We need to merge two data sets
2. We havent create our dependent variable
3. Each user had several different loans, the overdue status for each of their loans is also different. 

# Generally, users in risk should be in 3%, thus we choose users who overdue for more than 60 days as target risky users. Those samples are marked as '1', else are '0'.

# For loans that overdue by more than 60 days, we mark them as '1', else are '0'
credit_record[,'target'] <- 0
credit_record[credit_record[, 'STATUS'] == 2, 'target'] <- 1
credit_record[credit_record[, 'STATUS'] == 3, 'target'] <- 1
credit_record[credit_record[, 'STATUS'] == 4, 'target'] <- 1
credit_record[credit_record[, 'STATUS'] == 5, 'target'] <- 1

# We group by ID to see how many overdue loans(> 60 days) does each user have
credit_record <- credit_record %>% 
                 group_by(ID) %>% 
                 summarise(count = sum(target == 1))

# For those who have at least one overdue loans(> 60 days) we mark them as '1'(target risky users)
credit_record[credit_record$count > 0, 'count'] <- 1
# Then we merge two data sets
total_data <- merge(x=application_record,y=credit_record,by="ID",all=FALSE)

# Rename our dependent variable as 'target'
names(total_data)[names(total_data) == "count"] <- "target"
# Check our final data

# Modify some of the variables
# Change the scale of annual income to 1000
total_data$AMT_INCOME_TOTAL <- total_data$AMT_INCOME_TOTAL / 1000

# Change DAYS_BIRTH to AGE
total_data$DAYS_BIRTH <- (-total_data$DAYS_BIRTH) %/% 365
names(total_data)[names(total_data) == "DAYS_BIRTH"] <- "AGE"

# Change DAYS_EMPLOYED to WORKING_YEARS
total_data$DAYS_EMPLOYED <- (-total_data$DAYS_EMPLOYED) %/% 365
names(total_data)[names(total_data) == "DAYS_EMPLOYED"] <- "WORKING_YEARS"
# For currently unemployed people, set their working years as mean working years
mean_working_years <- round(mean(total_data[total_data$WORKING_YEARS > 0, 'WORKING_YEARS']), 0)
total_data[total_data$WORKING_YEARS < 0, 'WORKING_YEARS'] <- mean_working_years

After modification:
AMT_INCOME_TOTAL - Annual income in thousands
AGE - Users age
WORKING_YEARS - Users working years 

# Data Partition
set.seed(12345)
total_data <- total_data[,-c(1,13)] # delete ID and FLAG_MOBIL
total_data$FLAG_WORK_PHONE <- as.factor(total_data$FLAG_WORK_PHONE)
total_data$FLAG_PHONE <- as.factor(total_data$FLAG_PHONE)
total_data$FLAG_EMAIL <- as.factor(total_data$FLAG_EMAIL)
total_data$target <- as.factor(total_data$target)
indices <- createDataPartition(1:nrow(total_data), p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- total_data[indices,]
test_data <- total_data[-indices,]
# Check missing training data

# Do densities
plot_dat <- total_data 
plot_dat$target <- as.factor(total_data$target) 
g_1 <- ggplot(plot_dat, aes(x = AMT_INCOME_TOTAL, fill = target)) + 
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5) + 
    theme_set(theme_bw(base_size = 10) ) +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank(), 
        panel.background = element_blank()) +
  labs(x = "Total Income(in thousands)", title = "Total Income - Risky Users v Not Risky Users",
       fill = "Target") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("1" = "red", "0" = "blue"), 
                    labels = c("1" = "Risky Users", "0" = "Not Risky Users"))

# Use ROSE to balance data
library(ROSE)
## Loaded ROSE 0.0-4
over_data <- ovun.sample(target~., data = train_data, method = 'over', N = 28663*2)$data
table(over_data$target)

Logistic Regression

# Logistic Regression
lm_full <- glm(target~., family = 'binomial', data = over_data)

lm_full_pred <- predict(lm_full, newdata = test_data, type = 'response')

lm_full_acc <- confusionMatrix(factor(ifelse(lm_full_pred>0.5, '1', '0')), test_data$target, positive = '1')

Lasso

over_data_mod <- model.matrix(target~., data=over_data)[,-1]
test_data_mod <- model.matrix(target~., data=test_data)[,-1]
x_data <- as.data.frame(scale(over_data_mod)) # Scale dataset
x_data$target <- over_data$target 
library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## 
## Attaching package: 'Matrix'
## The following object is masked from 'package:reshape':
## 
##     expand
## Loaded glmnet 4.1-2
library(plotmo)
## Loading required package: Formula
## Loading required package: plotrix
## Loading required package: TeachingDemos
# Create x variables
x_vars <- model.matrix(target ~., 
                       x_data)[,-1]
# Fit lasso model
lasso_fit <- glmnet(x = x_vars, # Set explantory variables
                    y = over_data$target, # Set response variable
                    alpha = 1, # Set alpha value
                    family = "binomial")
plot_glmnet(lasso_fit, # Plot lasso coefficients by lambda
            xvar = "lambda")

# Print coefficients
coef(lasso_fit)

## `OCCUPATION_TYPESecurity staff`                     0.0381120536  0.038376684
## `OCCUPATION_TYPEWaiters/barmen staff`               0.0087552301  0.008939142
## CNT_FAM_MEMBERS                                     0.2009422151  0.202063264
# Tune lambda
set.seed(11111)
# Set sequence of lambda values
lambda_seq <- 10^seq(4, -4, by = -.1)
# Fit cross-validated lasso model
cv.lasso <- cv.glmnet(x = x_vars, # Set x variables
                 y = over_data$target, # Set response variables
                 alpha = 1, # Set alpha = 1 for lasso
                 family = "binomial", # Set family as binomial for logistic regression
                 lambda = lambda_seq, # Set lambda values to try
                 nfolds = 10)
best_lam <- cv.lasso$lambda.1se # Extract best lambda
best_lam  # Print best lambda
## [1] 0.001584893
lasso_fit_final <- glmnet(x = x_vars, # Set explantory variables
                    y = over_data$target, # Set response variable
                    alpha = 1, # Set alpha as 1 for lasso
                    family = "binomial", # Set as logistic regression
                    lambda = best_lam) # Set lambda as best lambda
# Compare our coefficients for both logistic and linear regression
temp <- cbind.data.frame(coef(lm_full), as.vector(coef(lasso_fit_final))) # Join Coefficients from models
names(temp) <- c("logisitic Regression", "Logistic Lasso") # Name coefficient columns
rownames(temp) <- names(coef(lm_full)) # Add rownames to coefficients
temp # Print coefficients

# Parameter tuning
trees <- c(10, 25, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000) # Create vector of possible tree sizes
nodesize <- c(1, 10, 25, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000) # Create vector of possible node sizes

params <- expand.grid(trees, nodesize) # Expand grid to get data frame of parameter combinations
names(params) <- c("trees", "nodesize") # Name parameter data frame
res_vec <- rep(NA, nrow(params)) # Create vector to store accuracy results

for(i in 1:nrow(params)){ # For each set of parameters
  set.seed(11111) # Set seed for reproducability
  mod <- randomForest(target ~. , # Set formula
                      data=over_data,# Set data
                      mtry = 16, # Set number of variables
                      importance = FALSE,  # 
                      ntree = params$trees[i], # Set number of trees
                      nodesize = params$nodesize[i]) # Set node size
  res_vec[i] <- 1 - mod$err.rate[nrow(mod$err.rate),1] # Calculate out of bag accuracy
}
summary(res_vec) # Summarize accuracy results
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.7645  0.9123  0.9769  0.9434  0.9837  0.9838
res_db <- cbind.data.frame(params, res_vec) # Join parameters and accuracy results
names(res_db)[3] <- "oob_error" # Name accuracy results column
res_db # Print accuracy results column

test_data_mod <- model.matrix(target~., data=test_data)[,-1]
# Create training matrix
dtrain <- xgb.DMatrix(data = train_data_mod, label = as.numeric(train_data$target) - 1)
# Create test matrix
dtest <- xgb.DMatrix(data = test_data_mod, label = as.numeric(test_data$target) - 1)
# Use weight parameter to balance data
# Create weight vector
one_weight <- 28663/505 # Calculate proportion of positive samples in data
weight_vec <- rep(1, nrow(train_data)) # Create weight vector
weight_vec[which(train_data$target == 1)] <- one_weight # Assign weight for positive samples

sum(weight_vec[which(train_data$target == 1)]) # Check 1 class weight
## [1] 28663
sum(weight_vec[which(train_data$target == 0)]) # Check 0 class weight
## [1] 28663
set.seed(111111)
bst_weight <- xgboost(data = dtrain, # Set training data
                      nrounds = 100, # Set number of rounds
                      verbose = 1, # 1 - Prints out fit
                      print_every_n = 20, # Prints out result every 20th iteration
                      weight = weight_vec,
                      objective = "binary:logistic", # Set objective
                      eval_metric = "auc",
                      eval_metric = "error") # Set evaluation metric to use

boost_preds_weight <- predict(bst_weight, dtest) # Create predictions for xgboost model
# Use scale_pos_weight parameter to balance data
set.seed(111111)
bst_scale <- xgboost(data = dtrain, # Set training data
                     nrounds = 100, # Set number of rounds
                     verbose = 1, # 1 - Prints out fit
                     print_every_n = 20, # Prints out result every 20th iteration
                     scale_pos_weight = sqrt(28663/505),

                     eval_metric = "auc",

# Tune max_depth_vals and min_child_weight
max_depth_vals <- c(3, 5, 7, 10, 15) # Create vector of max depth values
min_child_weight <- c(1, 3, 5, 7, 10, 15) # Create vector of min child values

# Expand grid of parameter values
cv_params <- expand.grid(max_depth_vals, min_child_weight)
names(cv_params) <- c("max_depth", "min_child_weight")
# Create results vector
auc_vec <- error_vec <- rep(NA, nrow(cv_params)) 
# Loop through results
for(i in 1:nrow(cv_params)){
  set.seed(111111)
  bst_tune <- xgb.cv(data = dtrain, # Set training data
                     nfold = 5, # Use 5 fold cross-validation
                     scale_pos_weight = sqrt(28663/505),
                     eta = 0.01, # Set learning rate
                     max.depth = cv_params$max_depth[i], # Set max depth
                     min_child_weight = cv_params$min_child_weight[i], # Set minimum number of samples in node to split
                     nrounds = 1000, # Set number of rounds
                     early_stopping_rounds = 50, # Set number of rounds to stop at if there is no improvement
                     verbose = 1, # 1 - Prints out fit
                     nthread = 1, # Set number of parallel threads
                     print_every_n = 20, # Prints out result every 20th iteration
                     objective = "binary:logistic", # Set objective
                     eval_metric = "auc", # Set evaluation metric to use
                     eval_metric = "error") # Set evaluation metric to use
  auc_vec[i] <- bst_tune$evaluation_log$test_auc_mean[bst_tune$best_ntreelimit]
  error_vec[i] <- bst_tune$evaluation_log$test_error_mean[bst_tune$best_ntreelimit]
  
}

# Tune gamma
gamma_vals <- c(0, 0.05, 0.1, 0.15, 0.2) # Create vector of gamma values

# Be Careful - This can take a very long time to run
set.seed(111111)
auc_vec <- error_vec <- rep(NA, length(gamma_vals))
for(i in 1:length(gamma_vals)){
  bst_tune <- xgb.cv(data = dtrain, # Set training data
                     nfold = 5, # Use 5 fold cross-validation
                     scale_pos_weight = sqrt(28663/505),
                     eta = 0.01, # Set learning rate
                     max.depth = 15, # Set max depth
                     min_child_weight = 7, # Set minimum number of samples in node to split
                     gamma = gamma_vals[i], # Set minimum loss reduction for split
                     nrounds = 1000, # Set number of rounds
                     early_stopping_rounds = 50, # Set number of rounds to stop at if there is no improvement
                     verbose = 1, # 1 - Prints out fit
                     nthread = 1, # Set number of parallel threads
                     print_every_n = 20, # Prints out result every 20th iteration
                     objective = "binary:logistic", # Set objective
                     eval_metric = "auc", # Set evaluation metric to use
                     eval_metric = "error") # Set evaluation metric to use
  auc_vec[i] <- bst_tune$evaluation_log$test_auc_mean[bst_tune$best_ntreelimit]
  error_vec[i] <- bst_tune$evaluation_log$test_error_mean[bst_tune$best_ntreelimit]
  
}

# Tune subsample and colsample_by_tree
subsample <- c(0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 1) # Create vector of subsample values
colsample_by_tree <- c(0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9, 1) # Create vector of col sample values

# Expand grid of tuning parameters
cv_params <- expand.grid(subsample, colsample_by_tree)
names(cv_params) <- c("subsample", "colsample_by_tree")
# Create vectors to store results
auc_vec <- error_vec <- rep(NA, nrow(cv_params)) 
# Loop through parameter values
for(i in 1:nrow(cv_params)){
  set.seed(111111)
  bst_tune <- xgb.cv(data = dtrain, # Set training data
                     nfold = 5, # Use 5 fold cross-validation
                     eta = 0.01, # Set learning rate
                     scale_pos_weight = sqrt(28663/505),
                     max.depth = 15, # Set max depth
                     min_child_weight = 7, # Set minimum number of samples in node to split
                     gamma = 0.2, # Set minimum loss reduction for split
                     subsample = cv_params$subsample[i], # Set proportion of training data to use in tree
                     colsample_bytree = cv_params$colsample_by_tree[i], # Set number of variables to use in each tree
                     nrounds = 1000, # Set number of rounds
                     early_stopping_rounds = 50, # Set number of rounds to stop at if there is no improvement
                     verbose = 1, # 1 - Prints out fit
                     nthread = 1, # Set number of parallel threads
                     print_every_n = 20, # Prints out result every 20th iteration
                     objective = "binary:logistic", # Set objective
                     eval_metric = "auc", # Set evaluation metric to use
                     eval_metric = "error") # Set evaluation metric to use
  auc_vec[i] <- bst_tune$evaluation_log$test_auc_mean[bst_tune$best_ntreelimit]
  error_vec[i] <- bst_tune$evaluation_log$test_error_mean[bst_tune$best_ntreelimit]
  
}

res_db <- cbind.data.frame(cv_params, auc_vec, error_vec)
names(res_db)[3:4] <- c("auc", "error")

res_db$colsample_by_tree <- as.factor(res_db$colsample_by_tree) # Convert node size to factor for plotting
g_4 <- ggplot(res_db, aes(y = colsample_by_tree, x = subsample, fill = auc)) + # set aesthetics
  geom_tile() + # Use geom_tile for heatmap
  theme_bw() + # Set theme
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", # Choose low color
    mid = "white", # Choose mid color
    high = "red", # Choose high color
    midpoint =mean(res_db$auc), # Choose mid point
    space = "Lab", 
    na.value ="grey", # Choose NA value
    guide = "colourbar", # Set color bar
    aesthetics = "fill") + # Select aesthetics to apply
  labs(x = "Subsample", y = "Column Sample by Tree", fill = "AUC") # Set labels

bst_mod_5 <- xgb.cv(data = dtrain, # Set training data
                    nfold = 5, # Use 5 fold cross-validation
                    eta = 0.001, # Set learning rate
                    max.depth = 15, # Set max depth
                    min_child_weight = 7, # Set minimum number of samples in node to split
                    gamma = 0.2, # Set minimum loss reduction for split
                    subsample = 0.7, # Set proportion of training data to use in tree
                    colsample_bytree =  0.7, # Set number of variables to use in each tree
                    scale_pos_weight = sqrt(28663/505),
                    nrounds = 1000, # Set number of rounds
                    early_stopping_rounds = 50, # Set number of rounds to stop at if there is no improvement
                    verbose = 1, # 1 - Prints out fit
                    nthread = 1, # Set number of parallel threads
                    print_every_n = 20, # Prints out result every 20th iteration
                    objective = "binary:logistic", # Set objective
                    eval_metric = "auc",
                    eval_metric = "error") # Set evaluation metric to use

# Final XGBoost model
set.seed(11111)
bst_final <- xgboost(data = dtrain, # Set training data
                     nrounds = 100, # Set number of rounds
                     verbose = 1, # 1 - Prints out fit
                     print_every_n = 20, # Prints out result every 20th iteration
                     eta = 0.005,
                     scale_pos_weight = sqrt(28663/505),
                     max.depth = 15,
                     min_child_weight = 7,
                     gamma = 0.2,
                     subsample = 0.7, # Set proportion of training data to use in tree
                     colsample_bytree =  0.7, # Set number of variables to use in each tree
                     objective = "binary:logistic", # Set objective
                     eval_metric = "auc",
                     eval_metric = "error") # Set evaluation metric to use
## [1]  train-auc:0.848677  train-error:0.037233 
## [21] train-auc:0.971934  train-error:0.016011 
## [41] train-auc:0.977945  train-error:0.015702 
## [61] train-auc:0.979553  train-error:0.015634 
## [81] train-auc:0.980109  train-error:0.015668 
## [100]    train-auc:0.981054  train-error:0.015702
# Find the optimal cutoff point
boost_preds_final <- predict(bst_final, dtest) # Create predictions for xgboost model
cutoff_seq <- seq(0.32,0.5,0.0001)
acc_vec <- sen_vec <- rep(NA, length(cutoff_seq))
for(i in 1:length(cutoff_seq)){
  boost_pred_class <- rep(0, length(boost_preds_final))
  boost_pred_class[boost_preds_final >= cutoff_seq[i]] <- 1
  t <- table(boost_pred_class, test_data$target)
  c <- confusionMatrix(t, positive = "1")
  acc_vec[i] <- c$overall[1]
  sen_vec[i] <- c$byClass[1]
}

res_db1 <- cbind.data.frame(cutoff_seq, acc_vec, sen_vec)
names(res_db1)[1:3] <- c("cutoff_point", "accuracy", "sensitivity") 
# Plot accuracy vs sensitivity for different cutoff points
g_as <- ggplot(res_db1, aes(x = sensitivity, y = accuracy, color = cutoff_point)) +
       geom_point(size = 2) +
       scale_color_gradient2(midpoint=mean(res_db1$cutoff_point), 
                             low="green", 
                             mid="yellow",
                             high="red",
                             space='Lab') +
       stat_smooth(geom='line', alpha=0.2, se=FALSE, size = 2) +
       labs(x = "Sensitivity", y = "Accuracy", color = "Cutoff Point")
g_as

# Compare ROC curves of all the models used
roc1 = roc(test_data$target, boost_preds_1)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc2 = roc(test_data$target, boost_preds_final)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc3 = roc(test_data$target, bag_preds_prob[,2])
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc4 = roc(test_data$target, lm_full_pred)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
roc5 = roc(test_data$target, gam1_pred)
## Setting levels: control = 0, case = 1
## Setting direction: controls < cases
# Print XGBoost initial model AUC
plot.roc(roc1, print.auc = TRUE, print.auc.x = 1, print.auc.y = 0.8, col = "cadetblue2", print.auc.col = "cadetblue2", auc.in.legend = TRUE)
# Print XGBoost final model AUC
plot.roc(roc2, print.auc = TRUE, print.auc.x = 1, print.auc.y = 0.9, col ="cadetblue", print.auc.col = "cadetblue", add = TRUE)
# Print Random Forest AUC
plot.roc(roc3, print.auc = TRUE, print.auc.x = 1, print.auc.y = 0.5, col ="lightgreen", print.auc.col = "lightgreen", add = TRUE)
# Print Logistic Regression AUC
plot.roc(roc4, print.auc = TRUE, print.auc.x = 0.5, print.auc.y = 0.5, col ="lightpink", print.auc.col = "lightpink", add = TRUE)
# Print GAM AUC
plot.roc(roc5, print.auc = TRUE, print.auc.x = 0.5, print.auc.y = 0.6, col ="lightpink3", print.auc.col = "lightpink3", add = TRUE)
